# DwarfSpec component-testing refactor

## Goal

Replace the fixture-oriented live UI API with a Cypress-style component-testing
model. A test mounts one DFHack UI component into a DwarfSpec-owned live
harness, and all later commands implicitly operate on that mount or on a fluent
subject selected from it.

The refactor is complete when ordinary widgets, overlay widgets, and complete
screens all use the same `ds.mount()` entry point; consumers do not implement
render counters; and tests do not pass fixture screens or raw views between
normal `ds` commands.

## Decisions

- Busted remains responsible for discovery, suites, examples, hooks,
  assertions, and result classification.
- DwarfSpec commands retain synchronous-looking coroutine semantics. This work
  does not introduce Cypress's deferred JavaScript command queue.
- `ds.mount(component, options)` is the only component mount operation.
- A mount accepts an ordinary `widgets.Widget`, an `overlay.OverlayWidget`, or
  a complete `gui.ZScreen`, either as a supported constructor/class or as an
  already-created instance.
- DwarfSpec owns the mount harness, render instrumentation, current-mount
  context, synchronization, diagnostics, and cleanup.
- A Busted example has at most one active mount. Calling `ds.mount()` while a
  component remains mounted is an error; the test must call `ds.unmount()`
  before mounting another component.
- `ds.get(control_path)` traverses direct children from the current mounted
  component and returns a DwarfSpec subject, not a raw DFHack view.
- Subject commands are fluent, for example `ds.get('submit'):click()`.
- Busted and Luassert remain the assertion API. DwarfSpec subjects expose
  stable values and diagnostics for assertions but do not add a parallel
  `should()` assertion language.
- Render generations are private DwarfSpec state. Consumers never add or
  maintain a `render_generation` field.
- Overlay widgets use `ds.mount()` like every other component. Any helper for
  proving overlay script discovery, configuration, or registration is an
  integration facility, not a separate overlay mount operation.
- Test-support factories remain ordinary Lua helpers. There is no required
  DwarfSpec fixture-module protocol or mandatory fixture directory.

## Target authoring experience

```lua
local TooltipOverlay =
    reqscript('gui/dwarfui-tooltip').OVERLAY_WIDGETS.tooltip

describe('tooltip overlay', function()
    before_each(function()
        ds.mount(TooltipOverlay, {
            message='Example tooltip',
        })
    end)

    it('shows its tooltip while hovering', function()
        ds.get('trigger'):hover()

        local tooltip = ds.await('tooltip becomes visible', function()
            local subject = ds.get('tooltip')
            return subject:inspect().visible and subject
        end)

        assert.equals('Example tooltip', tooltip:text())
    end)
end)
```

Escape hatches such as `subject:raw()` may expose a native object for uncommon
product-specific assertions, but ordinary selection and interaction must not
require raw views.

## Public API target

- mount context: `ds.mount`, `ds.root`, `ds.unmount`;
- selection: `ds.get`;
- synchronization: `ds.await`, `ds.wait_frames`;
- subject interaction: `click`, `hover`, `move_pointer`, `input`, `type`;
- subject observation: `inspect`, `text`, and an explicit raw-view escape
  hatch;
- evidence: mount-scoped view-tree and screen capture commands.

The final method names and return values must be documented and covered by
contract tests before the legacy fixture API is removed.

## Phase 1: Characterize the component boundary

- [x] Add unit characterization for constructing and identifying a plain
  `widgets.Widget`, an `overlay.OverlayWidget`, and a `gui.ZScreen`.
- [x] Define unambiguous rules for constructor/class inputs versus component
  instances and reject unsupported values with actionable errors.
- [x] Define the mount options common to every component, including viewport
  size, component attributes, initial pause behavior, and optional backing
  viewscreen context.
- [x] Define whether constructor failures, initialization failures, and first
  render failures are reported as mount failures or host errors.
- [x] Record the minimum DFHack APIs required by the live mount adapters.
- [x] Add a public API contract test that reserves `mount`, `root`, `unmount`,
  and the initial subject methods.

Exit evidence:

- [x] The three supported component categories and both supported input forms
  have executable contract tests.
- [x] No adapter behavior depends on product-specific classes or paths.

Phase 1 evidence (2026-07-20):

- `src/dwarfspec/component.lua` classifies callable DFHack `defclass` tables
  before invoking them. Arbitrary functions are not constructors in this
  contract because their category cannot be known before consumer code runs.
  Existing instances are recognized from their class metatable. Overlay
  classification precedes widget classification because `OverlayWidget`
  derives from `Widget`.
- Class inputs receive top-level, non-reserved mount options as constructor
  attributes. Existing instances accept harness options but reject constructor
  attributes instead of mutating an initialized component. Unsupported
  scalars, tables, classes, and factories produce errors that list the three
  supported DFHack bases and the accepted input forms.
- Common options are `viewport={width=<positive integer>, height=<positive
  integer>}`, `initial_pause=<boolean>` (default `true`), and
  `backing_viewscreen=<DFHack viewscreen>`. A missing viewport means the
  deterministic 128 by 64 DF-cell default. A complete screen class receives the
  normalized pause choice during construction; later host adapters own the
  equivalent behavior for widgets and overlays.
- Construction, DFHack `preinit`/`init`/`postinit`, and the first completed
  render belong to the mount operation and are reported as mount failures.
  Failures in DwarfSpec scheduling, cleanup infrastructure, or run ownership
  are host errors. `FAILURE_OWNERSHIP` and its unit contract reserve this
  distinction before render adapters are implemented.
- Minimum checked-out DFHack APIs were verified in `dfhack-53.15-r1`:
  callable classes plus `super`, `ATTRS`, `__index`, and instance metatables in
  `library/lua/class.lua`; `widgets.Widget` and the native view tree/layout,
  frame-body, render, visibility, activation, focus, and input contracts in
  `library/lua/gui/widgets/widget.lua` and `library/lua/gui.lua`;
  `overlay.OverlayWidget`, its positioning/painter attributes, and
  `overlay_onenable`, `overlay_onupdate`, `onInput`, and
  `overlay_ondisable` in `plugins/lua/overlay.lua`; and `gui.ZScreen` with
  `show`, `dismiss`, `isActive`, `onResize`, `onRender`, `onInput`, native
  viewscreen ownership, parent input forwarding, and pause restoration in
  `library/lua/gui.lua`.
- `tests/component_boundary_test.lua` executes class and instance cases for
  generic widget, overlay, and screen subclasses without importing any
  consumer module or path. It also covers overlay precedence, option defaults
  and validation, deterministic instance-attribute rejection, unsupported
  inputs, constructor/init failures, and reserved public method names.
  `tests/extensions_test.lua` proves a consumer cannot replace `ds.mount`, and
  `tests/package_contract_test.lua` proves the installed-module mapping exists.
- Verification: `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` reported 81 successes, 0 failures,
  and 0 errors; `tools/Check-Lua.ps1` parsed and formatting-checked all 65 Lua
  files with Lua 5.4.6; `luarocks lint dwarfspec-0.1.0-1.rockspec` passed; and
  `git diff --check` passed. A separate clean-tree `luarocks make` package
  smoke remains open for the release-proof work: local LuaRocks 3.9.2 aborts
  before building with `Error: File exists` while creating the new tree's
  `lib/luarocks/rocks-5.4/dwarfspec/0.1.0-1/conf` directory.

## Phase 2: Build the run-owned mount context

- [x] Add a mount-context module owned by one automation run.
- [x] Track the current mount, root component, host screen, private render
  generation, selected subjects, and cleanup entries without storing test
  metadata on consumer components.
- [x] Implement `ds.mount(component, options)` and `ds.unmount()` against the
  mount context.
- [x] Implement `ds.root()` as a subject for the current component root.
- [x] Make all mount-context references weak where ownership does not require a
  strong reference.
- [x] Reject a second `ds.mount()` before classification or construction while
  preserving the current mount; require explicit `ds.unmount()` first.
- [x] Produce clear errors for `root`, `get`, interaction, or unmount commands
  when no component is mounted.
- [x] Register mount cleanup before showing or activating a component so a
  partial mount failure remains reversible.

Exit evidence:

- [x] Unit tests cover initial mount, rejected second mount, explicit unmount,
  a later mount, partial mount failure, and operations without a current mount.
- [x] Cleanup leaves no active screen or pending mount entry after every case.

Phase 2 evidence (2026-07-20):

- `src/dwarfspec/mount_context.lua` creates one context from the automation
  run, its cleanup registry, the component boundary, an adapter factory, and a
  subject factory. Its single `current` record owns the mount identity,
  component category and class, root, host screen, private render generation,
  normalized options, adapter, weak selected-subject set, cleanup marker, and
  cleanup entries. Unit assertions confirm no mount id, host, cleanup list, or
  render generation is written onto the consumer root.
- `src/dwarfspec/subject.lua` stores only a scalar mount id plus weak values for
  its context, mount, and native object. The context's subject map and each
  mount's selected-subject set use weak keys. The current mount retains strong
  root, host, and adapter references only while lifecycle ownership requires
  them; cleanup clears those references and the implicit current mount.
- `tests/automation/support/cleanup.lua` now exposes a monotonic marker and
  `run_from()` scoped drain. Explicit unmount and failed mount rollback drain
  entries newer than the mount marker in strict LIFO order,
  without draining older run resources. The original run-wide `run()` remains
  the marker-zero form and stays idempotent.
- The context classifies before construction, registers its parent unmount
  action, and only then calls the category adapter. Adapters can register child
  cleanup entries through the context. Activation exceptions, invalid adapter
  results, and root-subject creation failures all take the same scoped rollback
  path and retain the originating error. Adapter teardown and settling both run
  before references are cleared, even if teardown itself reports a failure.
- A second mount call fails before classification or construction and leaves
  the current mount and its subjects active. After explicit unmount, cleanup
  observes `resource`, `unmount`, and `settle` before the next constructor and
  activation. A later constructor failure leaves no implicit mount and no
  pending mount-owned cleanup.
- `tests/automation/support/ds.lua` wires `ds.mount`, `ds.root`, and
  `ds.unmount` to the context. The one-argument `ds.get(view_id)` form selects
  from the implicit root and returns a subject; the legacy two-argument form
  remains available until consumer migration. Root, current-mount selection,
  and omitted-target interaction calls all instruct the author to call
  `ds.mount(component, options)` when no mount exists.
- `tests/mount_context_test.lua` covers initial mount, host and private state,
  second-mount rejection, stale subjects, explicit idempotent unmount, adapter
  activation failure, invalid adapter result, root-subject failure, failed
  construction after unmount, run cleanup, and no-mount errors.
  `tests/ds_mount_commands_test.lua` covers the public command wiring and
  implicit selection, including the explicit-unmount requirement. Every
  example has an unconditional registry drain that asserts `current == nil`,
  zero pending cleanup entries, and every created host inactive after the
  example.
- Verification: `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` reported 94 successes, 0 failures,
  and 0 errors; `tools/Check-Lua.ps1` parsed and formatting-checked all 69 Lua
  files with Lua 5.4.6; `luarocks lint dwarfspec-0.1.0-1.rockspec` passed; and
  `git diff --check` passed. `tests/package_contract_test.lua` verifies both
  new modules are present in the rockspec, and the isolated live export spec
  now reserves the three public mount functions for its later installed-rock
  run.

Contract revision evidence (2026-07-21):

- The mount context rejects a second call before component classification or
  construction. Context and public-command tests prove the rejection preserves
  the current screen, root, subject, mount identity, and cleanup entries. They
  then explicitly unmount and successfully mount the next component.
- `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passes 130 tests with no failures, errors, or
  pending tests. `tools/Check-Lua.ps1` passes Lua 5.4.6 syntax and formatting
  checks for all 82 Lua files.
- DFHack's embedded Lua 5.3 passes the focused 3-example ordinary-widget live
  spec and the complete 20-example product-independent live suite. Report
  `dwarfspec-158497593-46eec53a.json` records `state=passed`, zero failures and
  errors, `cleanup_confirmed=true`, lifecycle verification true, zero active
  screens, zero subjects, and no pointer patch.

## Phase 3: Own render instrumentation

- [x] Add a private render tracker that can wait for a generation greater than
  a captured generation without requiring a component field.
- [x] Instrument the DwarfSpec host screen's completed render path for mounted
  widgets and overlay widgets.
- [x] Instrument a mounted complete screen's effective `onRender` path without
  requiring the screen class to cooperate.
- [x] Preserve the original complete-screen render behavior and restore any
  instance interception during cleanup.
- [x] Increment generations only after successful completed renders.
- [x] Route mount, click, hover, input, type, resize, and other mutating
  operations through the private render tracker.
- [x] Capture bounded screen and component-tree diagnostics when mounting or
  rendering fails.
- [x] Remove the `render_generation` requirement from the public fixture and
  interaction contracts.

Exit evidence:

- [x] Live tests prove automatic generation changes for a plain widget, an
  overlay widget, and a complete screen whose source contains no DwarfSpec
  instrumentation.
- [x] A render failure retains the original error plus mount diagnostics.

Evidence (2026-07-20): `src/dwarfspec/render_tracker.lua` owns the private
generation and waits for a value strictly greater than its capture;
`src/dwarfspec/render_instrumentation.lua` reversibly intercepts the effective
instance `onRender`, preserves multiple return values and inherited or
instance behavior, records completion only after success, and retains failures
without advancing. `src/dwarfspec/mount_adapters.lua` applies that interception
to the DwarfSpec-owned widget/overlay host and directly to complete screens.
The mount context synchronizes activation and mutations, and `ds` routes
current-mount hover, click, input, type, and resize plus legacy fixture
interactions through DwarfSpec-owned trackers. Bounded 16x8 screen and
component-tree evidence is retained on the active run and included with the
original failure text. README and `docs/writing-tests.md` no longer require a
consumer render field or hook.

Focused unit contracts cover generation capture/completion/failure, reversible
inherited and instance interception, exact restoration, adapter ownership,
failed first render rollback, and mutation waits. The complete unit command
`tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passed with 106 successes, 0 failures, and 0 errors;
`tools/Check-Lua.ps1` parsed and formatting-checked 76 files with Lua 5.4.6;
the embedded DFHack Lua 5.3 runtime parsed and executed the new live modules;
`luarocks lint dwarfspec-0.1.0-1.rockspec` and `git diff --check` passed; and
the package contract verifies all three new modules in the rockspec. The
source-tree runner now passes its already-validated pure-Lua dependency root
to DFHack, so a local 5.4 dependency tree works without installing or loading
5.4 native modules in embedded Lua 5.3.

The product-independent live matrix mounts a plain widget class, an existing
overlay instance, and a complete screen class with no `render_generation` or
automation hook. Its widget case also completes hover, click, input, type, and
resize waits. A deliberately failing widget retains `deliberate component
render failure`, mount/category data, the component tree, and bounded screen
dimensions. The complete DwarfSpec live command with
`--test-glob '*_live_spec.lua'` passed 13 examples with 0 failures and 0 errors;
report `dwarfspec-93784984-008fd562.json` records `state=passed`,
`cleanup_confirmed=true`, and `cleanup_reason="suite completion"`.

## Phase 4: Implement the ordinary-widget adapter

- [x] Create a generic DwarfSpec `ZScreen` host for ordinary widgets.
- [x] Mount the component as the host's root content without mutating its class.
- [x] Propagate layout, visibility, activation, focus, input, and resize through
  normal DFHack widget behavior.
- [x] Ensure the mounted component receives a real painter and real live frame
  bodies.
- [x] Associate descendants with the owning mount automatically after layout
  and after dynamic subtree changes.
- [x] Restore the prior pause state and dismiss the host during unmount.

Exit evidence:

- [x] A live component test can mount a product-independent widget, locate a
  descendant, click it, type into it, inspect it, and unmount it without ever
  receiving or passing the host screen.

Evidence (2026-07-20): `src/dwarfspec/mount_adapters.lua` constructs one
private `gui.ZScreen` class, adds the ordinary component instance through
`addviews`, and delegates resize to the inherited screen implementation using
either the normalized fixed viewport or live dimensions. The adapter passes
the normalized pause and backing-viewscreen choices to the host and registers
dismissal before reversible render interception in LIFO cleanup order. It does
not assign methods or harness fields to the component or its class.

`src/dwarfspec/mount_context.lua` maintains weak view-to-mount ownership and a
run-owned ID index. The index is rebuilt from the ordered native tree after
the first layout/render, after each synchronized mutation, and in the render
completion callback before the new generation is published. Removed views are
disassociated and their subjects are rejected. Unit contracts cover initial,
nested, dynamically added, dynamically removed, and cleaned ownership plus
fixed viewport, backing viewscreen, pause-option forwarding, exact class
preservation, host dismissal, and completion-callback failure behavior.

`tests/automation/specs/ordinary_widget_mount_live_spec.lua` mounts both a
class and an existing product-independent `widgets.Panel` instance. Its nested
standard `EditField` and `HotkeyLabel` exercise real layout, visibility,
activation, focus, mouse input, text input, fixed and explicit resize, a real
`gui.Painter`, dynamic `addviews`, `ds.get(view_id)`, `ds.inspect`, and
`ds.unmount` without receiving or passing the host screen. Pause state is
unchanged after unmount, the component class remains unchanged, and the root
subject becomes stale. Source-tree live loading now prefers checked-out files
over a long-running DFHack process's module cache while installed layouts
continue to use `require`.

`tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passed with 110 successes, 0 failures, and 0 errors;
`tools/Check-Lua.ps1` parsed and formatting-checked 77 Lua files with Lua
5.4.6; the embedded DFHack Lua 5.3 runtime parsed and executed the new live
spec; `luarocks lint dwarfspec-0.1.0-1.rockspec` and `git diff --check` passed.
The complete source-tree live suite passed 15 examples with 0 failures and 0
errors. Report `dwarfspec-95309203-6885caaf.json` records `state=passed`,
`cleanup_confirmed=true`, and `cleanup_reason="suite completion"`.

## Phase 5: Implement the overlay-widget adapter

- [x] Accept `overlay.OverlayWidget` through the same `ds.mount()` dispatcher.
- [x] Reuse the generic host screen and private render tracker instead of
  installing a GUI script.
- [x] Assign an isolated run-owned logical name when the caller did not provide
  one.
- [x] Apply test-local frame positioning without reading or writing persisted
  overlay configuration.
- [x] Use the correct scaled, full-interface, or fullscreen painter contract.
- [x] Emulate applicable `overlay_onenable`, `overlay_onupdate`, `onInput`, and
  `overlay_ondisable` lifecycle calls in the same order as the DFHack overlay
  framework.
- [x] Supply an explicit backing viewscreen context to callbacks that normally
  receive one.
- [x] Cover visible, active, fullscreen, full-interface, update-throttled, and
  input-handling behavior.
- [x] Document that isolated mounting intentionally bypasses script discovery,
  persisted enablement and position, viewscreen/focus filtering, hotspot
  registration, and overlay database registration.

Exit evidence:

- [x] The same mount, selection, interaction, synchronization, and cleanup
  tests pass for ordinary and overlay widgets.
- [x] No public method named `mount_overlay`, `show_overlay_fixture`, or similar
  exists.

Phase 5 evidence (2026-07-20):

- `src/dwarfspec/overlay_mount.lua` owns the isolated logical name, copied
  frame positioning, scaled/fullscreen painter selection, throttled update,
  visible/active input gates, explicit backing viewscreen, lifecycle callbacks,
  and idempotent restoration. `mount_adapters.lua` routes overlays through the
  existing private component host and render instrumentation; it does not load
  or register a GUI script.
- `overlay_position={x=<integer>, y=<integer>}` is a reserved overlay-only
  harness option. Positive and negative coordinates match DFHack's one-based
  left/top and right/bottom anchors, while zero is normalized to one as the
  overlay framework does. Existing component names and frame tables are
  restored on unmount.
- `docs/writing-tests.md` documents isolated overlay mounting and explicitly
  lists the discovery, persisted configuration, viewscreen/focus filtering,
  hotspot, database-registration, and rescan behavior that it bypasses.
- `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passes 114 tests with no failures, errors, or
  pending tests. The focused overlay contracts cover names, positioning,
  scaled full-interface and fullscreen painters, visibility, activation,
  throttling, input, callback order, backing viewscreens, and idempotent
  cleanup.
- `tools/Check-Lua.ps1` passes Lua 5.4.6 syntax and formatting checks for 80
  Lua files. The focused overlay live suite passes 2 tests in DFHack's embedded
  Lua 5.3 for both a class and an existing instance. Its report has
  `cleanup_confirmed=true`.
- The complete product-independent live suite passes 17 tests with no failures
  or errors in run `dwarfspec-96956125-3c27fb4b`; its terminal report records
  `cleanup_confirmed=true` and `cleanup_reason="suite completion"`. An earlier
  run reached the scheduler diagnostic while the backing UI focus was
  `dwarfmode/AnnouncementAlert`; after restoring that test's documented
  `dwarfmode/Default` precondition, the final suite passed.
- The live export contract passes and proves `ds.mount` exists while
  `ds.mount_overlay` and `ds.show_overlay_fixture` are absent. The overlay live
  contract uses the same implicit selection, click, inspection, render wait,
  explicit unmount, and automatic cleanup paths as the ordinary-widget live
  contract.
- `luarocks lint dwarfspec-0.1.0-1.rockspec` passes. A local
  `luarocks make --pack-binary-rock --deps-mode none` succeeds, and the packed
  archive contains `lua/dwarfspec/overlay_mount.lua` and `rock_manifest`; the
  archive also installs successfully into an isolated local tree with
  dependency resolution disabled.
  Source-rock `luarocks pack` cannot clone the configured public source URL:
  GitHub returns `Repository not found` for
  `https://github.com/dsisco11/DwarfSpec.git`; this does not affect the local
  checkout package-content proof.

## Phase 6: Implement the complete-screen adapter

- [x] Accept `gui.ZScreen` through the same `ds.mount()` dispatcher.
- [x] Show the supplied screen directly rather than placing it inside another
  covering screen.
- [x] Install and remove automatic render interception on the mounted instance.
- [x] Preserve native screen activation, dismissal, parent input forwarding,
  and pause-state behavior.
- [x] Associate the complete screen and all descendants with the current mount.
- [x] Verify modal and child-screen behavior without allowing an unowned screen
  to become the implicit component root.

Exit evidence:

- [x] Complete-screen component tests use the same `ds.mount`, `ds.get`, and
  fluent subject commands as widget tests.
- [x] The tested screen has no test-only render counter or lifecycle hook.

Phase 6 evidence (2026-07-20):

- `src/dwarfspec/mount_adapters.lua` dispatches the `screen` category to the
  supplied `gui.ZScreen` instance itself. It installs private render
  interception and mount-owned viewport resize interception only on that
  instance, passes `backing_viewscreen` to its native `show()` method, and
  restores both intercepted methods after native dismissal. It does not create
  a covering host for complete screens or replace `onInput` or `dismiss`.
- `src/dwarfspec/mount_context.lua` keeps the mounted screen as the immutable
  implicit root and recursively indexes its ordered native view descendants.
  `tests/automation/support/ds.lua` routes input to the current native child
  only when its parent chain contains the mounted screen; this preserves modal
  input while an unrelated screen cannot become the component root.
- The reserved subject operations now forward synchronously to the existing
  run-owned commands. Mutating subject methods preserve the subject for fluent
  chaining, while `inspect()` and `text()` return stable observations. The
  ordinary-widget and complete-screen live contracts both use forms such as
  `ds.get('submit'):click()` and `ds.get('status'):text()` without a deferred
  command queue.
- `tests/automation/specs/complete_screen_mount_live_spec.lua` mounts both a
  class and an existing instance. It proves direct activation, nested
  descendant selection, mount-owned viewport behavior, automatic render-method
  restoration, native dismissal, parent pause-input forwarding, initial pause
  and restoration, fluent editing and clicking, and a modal child that handles
  input without changing `ds.root()` or making its `modal_only` view selectable.
- `tests/automation/specs/component_render_tracking_live_spec.lua` retains a
  minimal complete screen with no `onRender`, render counter, or automation
  lifecycle hook. DwarfSpec instruments and restores the instance without
  changing its class.
- `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passes 117 tests with no failures, errors, or
  pending tests. Focused contracts cover exact direct-screen identity,
  backing-screen and viewport forwarding, unchanged native input and dismissal
  methods, reversible interception, fluent subject returns and observations,
  and native-child input resolution that rejects unrelated screens.
- `tools/Check-Lua.ps1` passes Lua 5.4.6 syntax and formatting checks for 82
  Lua files. The focused complete-screen live suite passes two tests in
  DFHack's embedded Lua 5.3 and records `cleanup_confirmed=true` in run
  `dwarfspec-97791203-2fa9cf49`.
- The complete product-independent live suite passes 19 tests with no failures
  or errors in run `dwarfspec-97831000-60fd04c3`. Its terminal report records
  `cleanup_confirmed=true` and `cleanup_reason="suite completion"`.

## Phase 7: Add implicit selection and fluent subjects

- [x] Implement `ds.get(view_id)` against only the current mount's propagated
  view-id index.
- [x] Return a run-owned subject wrapper containing the selected view and mount
  identity.
- [x] Reject stale subjects after unmount.
- [x] Move view-oriented operations from `ds` functions onto subjects:
  `click`, `hover`, `move_pointer`, `input`, `type`, `inspect`, and `text`.
- [x] Make interaction methods return a useful subject so compatible commands
  can be chained.
- [x] Define when a command preserves the subject, changes it, or returns a
  scalar observation.
- [x] Keep command execution immediate within the live coroutine; do not add a
  deferred command queue.
- [x] Add `subject:raw()` as an explicitly documented escape hatch and ensure
  internal APIs never require callers to use it.
- [x] Make mount-scoped capture commands infer the current root.
- [x] Include the selected view id and current mount identity in failures and
  retained diagnostics.

Exit evidence:

- [x] Representative tests use `ds.get('id'):click()` and Busted assertions
  without passing a fixture, screen, root, or raw view to normal commands.
- [x] Unit tests cover fluent return behavior, stale subjects, duplicate ids,
  missing ids, and dynamic view-tree changes.

Phase 7 evidence (2026-07-20):

- `ds.get(view_id)` now accepts one view id, searches the refreshed index for
  the implicit current mount, and rejects missing or duplicate ids with the
  requested id and mount identity. The run-owned subject stores stable
  `view_id` and `mount_id` identity while retaining only weak native/context
  references.
- Subject commands execute immediately through the owning mount context.
  `click`, `hover`, `move_pointer`, `input`, and `type` preserve the subject;
  `inspect` returns a stable table and `text` returns its text scalar. No
  current command changes selection. `docs/writing-tests.md` and `README.md`
  document these semantics and reserve `raw()` for exceptional native access.
- Stale subjects are rejected after explicit unmount and dynamic subtree
  removal. Operational failures and retained mount evidence
  include the selected view id, its original mount id, and the current mount
  id. Mount-scoped `capture_view_tree(name)` infers the current component root;
  the legacy fixture capture form remains only for the pending fixture
  migration.
- Focused Busted runs pass 2 subject-command tests, 14 mount-context tests, and
  4 public mount-command tests. They cover immediate fluent returns and scalar
  observations, missing and duplicate ids, dynamic add/remove and duplicate
  recovery, stale raw and command access, implicit capture roots, and retained
  selection diagnostics.
- `tools/Run-UnitTests.ps1` passes 120 tests with no failures, errors, or
